---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Base
  title="InferNode Security — Formally Verified Namespace Isolation & Post-Quantum Crypto"
  description="InferNode's namespace isolation is formally verified using TLA+, SPIN, and CBMC: 12 properties, 113 checks, 0 failures. Plus experimental ML-KEM and ML-DSA post-quantum cryptography."
>
  <Nav />
  <main>

    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="relative flex items-center justify-center px-6 pt-40 pb-24 lg:pb-32">
      <div class="pointer-events-none absolute inset-0 bg-[radial-gradient(ellipse_at_center,_rgba(224,96,48,0.06)_0%,_transparent_70%)]"></div>
      <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center">
        <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Security</p>
        <h1 class="mb-6 text-4xl font-bold leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-5xl lg:text-6xl">
          Formally verified.<br /><span class="text-accent">Not just claimed.</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
          InferNode's namespace isolation is not a security policy layered on top of an existing OS.
          It is structural — and we have the proofs. Twelve properties verified across three tools,
          113 CBMC assertions, zero failures.
        </p>

        <!-- Stat row -->
        <div class="mt-10 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-8 text-sm">
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
            <span class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text">12</span>
            <span class="text-text-muted">properties verified</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hidden h-8 w-px bg-border sm:block self-center"></div>
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
            <span class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text">113</span>
            <span class="text-text-muted">CBMC checks, 0 failures</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hidden h-8 w-px bg-border sm:block self-center"></div>
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
            <span class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text">3</span>
            <span class="text-text-muted">independent tools</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hidden h-8 w-px bg-border sm:block self-center"></div>
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
            <span class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text">CI</span>
            <span class="text-text-muted">runs on every push</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Architecture: why it works -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="grid gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2 items-center">
          <div>
            <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">The Architecture</p>
            <h2 class="mb-6 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">If you didn't grant it, it doesn't exist.</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted">
              <p>
                Each agent runs in a <strong class="text-text">per-process namespace</strong> — a view of the
                filesystem constructed entirely from resources you explicitly mount into it.
                Your credentials, SSH keys, and email are not present in the agent's namespace.
                They do not produce an access-denied error. They simply <strong class="text-text">do not exist</strong>.
              </p>
              <p>
                This is not a sandbox bolted onto a conventional OS. It is how Inferno's kernel
                works, derived from Plan&nbsp;9's original namespace design. The isolation
                boundary is enforced by <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pgrpcpy()</code>
                in the kernel — a function we have verified at every level: abstract model,
                concurrent protocol, and real C code.
              </p>
              <p>
                Because the isolation is structural, prompt injection attacks that try to read
                outside the granted namespace are not just blocked — there is nothing to block.
                The path does not resolve. The attack surface is zero by construction.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Terminal -->
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface font-mono text-sm overflow-hidden">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 border-b border-border px-4 py-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full bg-node-rpi/60"></div>
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full bg-node-llm/60"></div>
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full bg-node-jetson/60"></div>
              <span class="ml-2 text-xs text-text-muted">agent namespace</span>
            </div>
            <div class="p-5 space-y-3">
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text-muted"> # grant only what the agent needs</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> mount /n/docs /agent/data</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> mount /n/llm /agent/llm</span></div>
              <div class="mt-4"><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text-muted"> # agent's entire world</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> ls /agent/</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-node-laptop">data/</span><span class="text-node-llm ml-4">llm/</span></div>
              <div class="mt-4"><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text-muted"> # prompt injection steals SSH keys?</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> cat /home/.ssh/id_rsa</span></div>
              <div class="text-text-muted italic">&nbsp;&nbsp;# path doesn't exist. nothing to steal.</div>
              <div class="mt-4"><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text-muted"> # exfiltrate /etc/passwd?</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> cat /etc/passwd</span></div>
              <div class="text-text-muted italic">&nbsp;&nbsp;# doesn't exist either. attack surface: zero.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Verification phases -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-12 text-center">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">The Proof</p>
          <h2 class="mb-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Five phases. Three tools. One conclusion.</h2>
          <p class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-text-muted">
            Verification proceeds from abstract model to locking protocol to real C code,
            with CI running checks automatically on every push.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <!-- Phase 1 -->
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-6">
              <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-accent/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-accent">TLA+ / SPIN</span>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">Phase 1 &mdash; Abstract Namespace Isolation</h3>
                <p class="mb-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                  Specifies namespace operations (<code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">Mount</code>,
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">PgrpCopy</code>,
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">Unmount</code>) at the abstract level using
                  history variables. Verifies the core isolation theorem: a channel mounted in the parent
                  <em>after</em> a copy does not appear in the child unless the child independently mounted it.
                  This is not tautologically true &mdash; it depends on the correctness of the implementation.
                </p>
                <div class="rounded-lg bg-bg px-4 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-text-muted">
                  <div class="text-text">NamespaceIsolation ==</div>
                  <div class="pl-4">&#8704; pg_child &isin; PgrpId :</div>
                  <div class="pl-8">active(pg_child) &and; active(pg_parent) &rArr;</div>
                  <div class="pl-12">post-copy mount in parent &NotElement; child mount table</div>
                </div>
                <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-text-muted">
                  Basic model: 83 states, 0 errors &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp;
                  Extended model (nested fork): 2,035 states, 0 errors
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Phase 2 -->
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-6">
              <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-node-rpi/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-node-rpi">SPIN</span>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">Phase 2 &mdash; Locking Protocol</h3>
                <p class="mb-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                  Models the two-lock protocol (<code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pg&rarr;ns</code>
                  and <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">m&rarr;lock</code>) with three concurrent
                  processes running all combinations of mount, unmount, copy, lookup, and close operations.
                  Verifies deadlock freedom, lock-ordering invariant, and reader/writer correctness including
                  the early-release optimisation in <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">cmount()</code>.
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-text-muted">
                  4,830 states, 10,095 transitions, 0 errors &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp;
                  LTL lock-ordering property verified &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp;
                  All 6 concurrent operation combinations tested
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Phase 3 -->
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-6">
              <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-node-jetson/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-node-jetson">CBMC</span>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">Phase 3 &mdash; Real C Code</h3>
                <p class="mb-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                  Bounded model checking directly on the kernel C implementation &mdash; not a model.
                  Three targeted harnesses verify array bounds (the MOUNTH macro, loop bounds in
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">closepgrp()</code> and
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pgrpcpy()</code>), integer overflow
                  safety in file descriptor allocation, and reference-count arithmetic.
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-text-muted">
                  113 assertions checked &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 0 failures &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp;
                  MOUNTH macro proven bounds-safe for all possible qid.path values by bitmasking argument
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Phases 4 & 5 -->
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-6">
              <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-node-cloud/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-node-cloud">SPIN</span>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">Phases 4 &amp; 5 &mdash; Race Conditions &amp; Export Boundary</h3>
                <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                  Phase 4 models concurrent access by
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">Sys_pctl</code>,
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">kchdir</code>, and
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">namec</code> to identify any data races at the
                  C/emu level (distinct from Inferno's cooperative Dis threading).
                  Phase 5 verifies the <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">exportfs</code> root
                  boundary: <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">walk("..")</code> cannot escape the
                  export root regardless of path depth.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Properties table -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-10 text-center">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Properties</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">What is verified, and how.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-surface">
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Property</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Description</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Tool</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-border">
              {[
                ['NamespaceIsolation', 'Post-copy mounts do not leak across namespaces', 'TLA+ / SPIN'],
                ['UnilateralMountNonPropagation', 'A unilateral mount never appears in the other namespace', 'TLA+'],
                ['CopyFidelity', 'pgrpcpy produces an exact duplicate of the source', 'TLA+ / CBMC'],
                ['PostCopyMountsSound', 'History variable tracking is accurate', 'TLA+'],
                ['MountLocalityProperty', 'Each step modifies at most one pgrp', 'TLA+'],
                ['RefCountNonNegative', 'Reference counts never go negative', 'TLA+ / CBMC'],
                ['NoUseAfterFree', 'Freed objects are never accessed', 'TLA+ / SPIN'],
                ['DeadlockFreedom', 'No concurrent namespace operation sequence deadlocks', 'SPIN'],
                ['LockOrdering', 'pg→ns always acquired before m→lock', 'SPIN'],
                ['ArrayBounds', 'MOUNTH macro always produces a valid array index', 'CBMC'],
                ['IntegerOverflow', 'File descriptor allocation arithmetic is safe', 'CBMC'],
                ['ExportBoundary', 'walk("..") cannot escape the exportfs root', 'SPIN'],
              ].map(([prop, desc, tool]) => (
                <tr class="bg-bg-surface hover:bg-bg-surface-hover transition">
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-accent">{prop}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 text-text-muted">{desc}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3">
                    <span class="rounded-full bg-accent/10 px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-accent">{tool}</span>
                  </td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- C code correspondence -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-10 text-center">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Implementation Fidelity</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Specifications correspond to real code.</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 mx-auto max-w-2xl text-text-muted">
            Every operation in the formal models maps to a specific C function in the kernel.
            CBMC verifies the actual source, not an abstraction.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-surface">
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Operation</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">C Function</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Source</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Verified By</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-border">
              {[
                ['NewPgrp', 'newpgrp()', 'emu/port/pgrp.c:8', 'TLA+'],
                ['PgrpCopy', 'pgrpcpy()', 'emu/port/pgrp.c:74', 'TLA+, SPIN, CBMC'],
                ['ClosePgrp', 'closepgrp()', 'emu/port/pgrp.c:23', 'TLA+, SPIN'],
                ['Mount', 'cmount()', 'emu/port/chan.c:388', 'TLA+, SPIN'],
                ['Unmount', 'cunmount()', 'emu/port/chan.c:502', 'TLA+, SPIN'],
                ['NameResolve', 'namec()', 'emu/port/chan.c:997', 'TLA+, SPIN (race)'],
                ['ChangeDir', 'kchdir()', 'emu/port/sysfile.c:142', 'TLA+, SPIN (race)'],
                ['ForkWithNewNS', 'Sys_pctl(NEWNS)', 'emu/port/inferno.c:855', 'TLA+, SPIN (race)'],
                ['ForkWithForkNS', 'Sys_pctl(FORKNS)', 'emu/port/inferno.c:869', 'TLA+, SPIN (race)'],
                ['ExportWalk', 'walk()', 'emu/port/chan.c:685', 'SPIN (export)'],
              ].map(([op, fn, src, tools]) => (
                <tr class="bg-bg-surface hover:bg-bg-surface-hover transition">
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-accent">{op}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-text">{fn}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-text-muted">{src}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 text-xs text-text-muted">{tools}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Post-Quantum Crypto -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-10 text-center">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Cryptography</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Built for the post-quantum era.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-8">
          <div class="flex flex-col gap-6 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-8">
            <div class="flex h-12 w-12 flex-shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-accent/10">
              <span class="text-xl text-accent">&#9883;</span>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="mb-3 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Quantum-Safe Cryptography</h3>
                <span class="rounded-full border border-accent/40 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-accent">experimental</span>
              </div>
              <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-text">ML-KEM &mdash; Key Encapsulation</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                    NIST FIPS&nbsp;203 (August 2024). Module-Lattice Key Encapsulation Mechanism
                    based on the MLWE problem. Implements ML-KEM-768 (Level&nbsp;3) and ML-KEM-1024
                    (Level&nbsp;5). Constant-time throughout.
                  </p>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-text">ML-DSA &mdash; Digital Signatures</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                    NIST FIPS&nbsp;204 (August 2024). Module-Lattice Digital Signature Algorithm
                    based on MLWE/MSIS. Implements ML-DSA-65 (Level&nbsp;3) and ML-DSA-87
                    (Level&nbsp;5). Heap-allocated to fit Inferno's 32&nbsp;KB thread stacks.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                This work is <em>not yet recommended for production</em>. Cryptographic agility
                is a first-class design goal: when classical public-key cryptography is broken,
                InferNode will already have a path forward on the same lightweight OS that
                protects your agents today.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Trusted Computing Base & Limitations -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-8">
            <h3 class="mb-4 font-semibold">Trusted Computing Base</h3>
            <p class="mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">The verification trusts:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
              {[
                'Hardware executes correctly',
                'The C compiler (gcc) is correct',
                'The host OS provides correct threading primitives',
                'The memory allocator returns valid memory or nil',
                'SPIN, CBMC, and TLC tools are correct',
                'Stubs in cbmc/stubs.h faithfully model kernel primitives',
              ].map((item) => (
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                  <span class="mt-1 text-accent">&#8227;</span>
                  <span>{item}</span>
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-8">
            <h3 class="mb-4 font-semibold">Known Limitations</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
              {[
                ['Bounded verification', 'TLA+/TLC and CBMC explore finite state spaces. Unbounded proofs would require interactive theorem proving (Isabelle/HOL).'],
                ['Abstraction gap', 'SPIN models abstract lock semantics; the RWlock implementation is not verified at assembly level.'],
                ['Race condition scope', 'Races in namespace_races.pml may be benign under Inferno\'s cooperative Dis threading but are real at the C/emu level.'],
                ['Finite process count', 'Locking verified with 3 concurrent processes; protocols are compositional so this is representative.'],
              ].map(([title, desc]) => (
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-text">{title}:</strong> {desc}
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center">
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Show your auditors the math.</h2>
        <p class="mb-8 text-text-muted">
          All specifications, harnesses, model checker scripts, and CI configuration are
          in the open-source repository. Run the verification yourself.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:justify-center">
          <a
            href="https://github.com/NERVsystems/infernode/tree/main/formal-verification"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-accent px-6 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-white transition hover:bg-accent/80"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
          >
            View formal verification &rarr;
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://github.com/NERVsystems/infernode"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-lg border border-border px-6 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-text-muted transition hover:border-accent hover:text-text"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
          >
            Browse the source &rarr;
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>
